<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[146,770,1516,1917]" box="[146,236,1516,1536]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[146,236,1516,1536]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[146,770,1516,1917]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
This species is distinguished by the vertical, somewhat thickened paramere (
<figureCitation box="[248,319,1575,1595]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[146,173,1782,1799]" captionTargetBox="[251,1275,171,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-82@14.[198,1389,147,1747]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 9. Niesthrea male genitalia. (A–B) N. josei Göllner-Scheiding:(A)Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) N. lateroloba, sp. nov.: (C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view. (E–F) N. louisianica Sailer: (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. parvaloba, sp. nov.: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385102/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
) with a large denticle at the base, the reduced median process with reduced lobes that are narrower or subequal to the width of a paramere, and the long lateral lobe that is higher than a paramere. The labium extends to the base or middle of abdominal segment III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[146,770,1516,1917]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
The parameres of 
<taxonomicName authority="Melo &amp; Henry, 2019" authorityName="Melo &amp; Henry" authorityYear="2019" box="[348,471,1721,1741]" class="Insecta" family="Rhopalidae" genus="Niesthrea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvaloba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[348,471,1721,1741]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">N. parvaloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[478,549,1722,1741]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[562,631,1721,1741]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[146,173,1782,1799]" captionTargetBox="[251,1275,171,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-82@14.[198,1389,147,1747]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 9. Niesthrea male genitalia. (A–B) N. josei Göllner-Scheiding:(A)Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) N. lateroloba, sp. nov.: (C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view. (E–F) N. louisianica Sailer: (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. parvaloba, sp. nov.: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385102/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
) are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[231,332,1751,1771]" class="Insecta" family="Rhopalidae" genus="Niesthrea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentata">
<emphasis box="[231,332,1751,1771]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">N. dentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[348,417,1751,1771]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[146,173,1928,1945]" captionTargetBox="[256,1294,302,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-83@13.[197,1390,293,1893]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 8. Niesthrea male genitalia.(A–B) N. dentata Chopra:(A) Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) Niesthrea digna Chopra:(C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view.(E–F) N. fenestrata (Signoret): (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. flava Grillo and Alayo: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385100" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385100/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[477,560,1751,1771]" class="Insecta" family="Rhopalidae" genus="Niesthrea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digna">
<emphasis box="[477,560,1751,1771]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">N. digna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[576,646,1751,1771]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[146,173,1928,1945]" captionTargetBox="[256,1294,302,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-83@13.[197,1390,293,1893]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 8. Niesthrea male genitalia.(A–B) N. dentata Chopra:(A) Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) Niesthrea digna Chopra:(C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view.(E–F) N. fenestrata (Signoret): (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. flava Grillo and Alayo: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385100" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385100/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
) in having a strong basal denticle or tooth. It is easily recognized by the narrow median lobe that is narrower or subequal to the lateral width of a paramere, whereas in the latter two species, the median lobe has widely flared lateral processes making it much broader than the lateral width of a paramere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[818,1444,147,876]" box="[818,947,147,170]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[818,1444,147,876]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis box="[818,866,181,201]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Head</emphasis>
: 
<materialsCitation collectionCode="III" collectorName="Antenna &amp; Segment I" county="Extending" location="Pale" municipality="Labium" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" specimenCount="1">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03B5885B226EFFAE5E8BFAED3A4CA045:8EC36F96226EFFAE5D68FF113C8AA3E0" box="[881,917,181,201]" county="Extending" municipality="Labium" name="Pale" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Pale</location>
yellowish brown, with a few small red spots, with numerous, long, erect, pale setae. 
<emphasis box="[1101,1170,210,230]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectingMunicipality box="[1101,1170,210,230]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Labium</collectingMunicipality>
</emphasis>
: 
<collectingCounty box="[1184,1273,210,230]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Extending</collectingCounty>
to base or middle of abdominal segment 
<collectionCode box="[1025,1047,241,260]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">III</collectionCode>
. 
<emphasis box="[1057,1131,240,260]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectorName box="[1057,1131,240,260]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Antenna</collectorName>
</emphasis>
: 
<collectorName box="[1145,1234,240,260]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Segment I</collectorName>
yellowish brown, with a dark brown dorsal and ventral streak on apical half
</materialsCitation>
; segments II and III yellowish brown, slightly dark brown at apex of each, and with an indistinct, dorsal and ventral, narrow, dark brown line on each, with scattered, relatively short, erect setae subequal to the diameter of the respective segments; segment IV brown, paler yellowish brown on base one fourth and vaguely so at apex, with short, dense, pale to darker brown setae. 
<emphasis box="[942,1031,446,464]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Pronotum</emphasis>
: Yellowish brown, with scattered, small, red spots, median line narrowly yellow; 
<materialsCitation location="Hemelyron" municipality="Claval" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
densely set with relatively short, erect setae. 
<taxonomicName authority=": Pale" authorityName="Pale" box="[921,1055,504,524]" class="Trilobita" family="Styginidae" genus="Scutellum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Corynexochida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[921,1006,504,524]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Scutellum</emphasis>
: Pale
</taxonomicName>
yellowish brown, with a few scattered, red spots. 
<emphasis box="[872,970,533,553]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03B5885B226EFFAE5E8BFAED3A4CA045:8EC36F96226EFFAE5D71FDB13CD5A100" box="[872,970,533,553]" municipality="Claval" name="Hemelyron" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Hemelyron</location>
</emphasis>
: 
<collectingMunicipality box="[980,1037,533,553]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Claval</collectingMunicipality>
and corial cells clear, veins and apex of corium yellowish brown, with only a few brown spots on 
<typeStatus box="[1261,1338,562,582]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">holotype</typeStatus>
male, more heavily spotted on females
</materialsCitation>
; 
<materialsCitation collectorName="Legs &amp; Pale" location="Ventral" municipality="Uniformly" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
membrane clear. 
<emphasis box="[1210,1339,592,612]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03B5885B226EFFAE5E8BFAED3A4CA045:8EC36F96226EFFAE5AA3FDF43BE6A14D" box="[1210,1273,592,612]" municipality="Uniformly" name="Ventral" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Ventral</location>
surface
</emphasis>
: 
<collectingMunicipality box="[1351,1442,592,612]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Uniformly</collectingMunicipality>
pale yellowish brown, including sternal areas, with scattered, small, red spots. 
<emphasis box="[876,917,651,669]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectorName box="[876,917,651,669]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Legs</collectorName>
</emphasis>
: 
<collectorName box="[930,966,650,670]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Pale</collectorName>
yellowish brown
</materialsCitation>
; femora and tibiae with numerous scattered dark brown spots; setae on femora shorter than diameter of segment, setae on tibiae short than to subequal to diameter of segment. 
<emphasis box="[818,940,738,758]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Male genitalia</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis box="[951,1032,739,757]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Paramere</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1042,1106,738,758]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[146,173,1782,1799]" captionTargetBox="[251,1275,171,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-82@14.[198,1389,147,1747]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 9. Niesthrea male genitalia. (A–B) N. josei Göllner-Scheiding:(A)Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) N. lateroloba, sp. nov.: (C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view. (E–F) N. louisianica Sailer: (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. parvaloba, sp. nov.: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385102/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
): Vertical, somewhat thickened, with a stout basal denticle. 
<emphasis box="[994,1104,768,788]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Median lobe</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1115,1179,768,788]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[146,173,1782,1799]" captionTargetBox="[251,1275,171,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-82@14.[198,1389,147,1747]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 9. Niesthrea male genitalia. (A–B) N. josei Göllner-Scheiding:(A)Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) N. lateroloba, sp. nov.: (C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view. (E–F) N. louisianica Sailer: (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. parvaloba, sp. nov.: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385102/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
): Small, narrower and shorter than a paramere, weakly constricted basally, lateral processes small, weakly flared. 
<emphasis box="[943,1047,826,846]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Lateral lobe</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1057,1180,826,846]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[146,173,1782,1799]" captionTargetBox="[251,1275,171,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-82@14.[198,1389,147,1747]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 9. Niesthrea male genitalia. (A–B) N. josei Göllner-Scheiding:(A)Ventral view.(B) Lateral view.(C–D) N. lateroloba, sp. nov.: (C)Ventral view.(D) Lateral view. (E–F) N. louisianica Sailer: (E) Ventral view. (F) Lateral view. (G–H) N. parvaloba, sp. nov.: (G) Ventral view. (H) Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385102/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig.9G and H</figureCitation>
): Extending above parameres, extremely broad at base and apically rounded in lateral aspect.
</paragraph>
